  "bib_entries": {
    "113822579": {
      "title": "Risk and Reliability",
      "abstract": "Risk and Reliability concepts are not generally understood by bridge engineers because they are not explicitly used in the everyday practice of bridge assessment or design. In the last decade or so, however, there seems to have been a growing appetite to understand both of the concepts, and the practical application of them in order to make more confident decisions about the maintenance requirements and priorities of a bridge stock. Very good overviews of the meaning and application of reliability methods have been produced by Bailey (1996) , Rosowsky (1997) and Melchers (1999) but essentially reliability is a probabilistic way of defining the limit states performance of a bridge system or bridge component. This is expressed as the probability of a certain event (limit state) occurring, the most important of which is that of collapse ."
    }
